Foundations of Temporal Contribution Dynamics: An Axiomatic and Spectral Approach using Geometric Embeddings and Kernel Methods for Knowledge Propagation in Epistemic Networks

Author: Ouadi Maakoul

Date: March 2026

---

Abstract

This thesis establishes a rigorous mathematical foundation for measuring persistent knowledge propagation in temporal epistemic networks. We define a Contribution Index (CI) as a functional on dynamic directed graphs, integrating temporal diffusion mechanisms with semantic originality constraints grounded in geometric embeddings and kernel density estimation. The core contribution is a system of coupled Volterra integro‑differential equations that models how ideas propagate and compound over time. We prove existence, uniqueness, and stability of solutions locally via the Banach fixed‑point theorem, and extend to global solutions via a priori bounds. We construct a discretized influence operator — the Epistemic Laplacian — and prove spectral gap conditions ensuring well‑posedness. Using matrix perturbation theory, we derive explicit sensitivity bounds on the Contribution Index under input perturbations.

For manipulation resistance, we prove that under a log‑damped semantic kernel with transaction‑value weighting, the internal amplification factor within a colluding cluster of $B$ nodes is $1 + O(\varepsilon B/\log(\varepsilon B))$, which reduces collusion gain from $O(B^2)$ to $O(\varepsilon B^2/\log(\varepsilon B))$ compared to undamped systems, within a precise convergence regime $\gamma \varepsilon (B-1)/(1+\log(\varepsilon B)) < 1$. Here $\varepsilon \in (0,1]$ represents the reputation weight of attacker nodes.

Novel theoretical enhancements include: (i) a knowledge recombination originality metric that captures relational novelty via Reference Knowledge Co‑occurrence Networks (RKCN) and Graph Attention Networks (GAT); (ii) spherical kernel density estimation with von Mises‑Fisher kernels for consistent density estimation on hyperspherical embeddings; (iii) a stochastic information geometry framework for distributed inference under uncertainty; (iv) a cold‑start validation methodology for new nodes using temporal graph networks; and (v) a spectral measure of epistemic emergence ($\Phi_{\text{spectral}}$) connecting the Contribution Index to system‑level irreducibility.

The framework is validated through mathematical analysis on canonical graph structures. This work provides the mathematical infrastructure for progress‑aware socio‑technical systems.


