Appendix D: Discretization Schemes for Spectral Analysis

D.1 Euler Discretization of the Volterra System

To facilitate spectral analysis in Section 4.2, we discretize the continuous system. Let $[0,T]$ be partitioned into $K$ steps of size $\Delta t = T/K$, with $t_k = k\Delta t$.

Definition D.1 (Discrete Influence). The discrete influence $I_j^k$ approximates $I_j(t_k)$ via:
I_j^{k+1} = I_j^k + \Delta t \left( \sum_{i \neq j} \sum_{\ell=0}^{k} A_{ij}(t_\ell, t_k) \Phi_i^\ell \Delta t - \lambda I_j^k \right). 

Definition D.2 (Discrete Contribution Index). The discrete index $C_i^k$ approximates $C_i(t_k)$ via:
C_i^{k+1} = C_i^k + \Delta t \, \Phi_i^k. 

Proposition D.1 (Consistency). As $\Delta t \to 0$, the discrete system converges to the continuous Volterra system with error $O(\Delta t)$.

Proof Sketch. Follows from standard consistency analysis of Euler methods for integro-differential equations (Brunner, 2004). The local truncation error is $O(\Delta t^2)$, and the global error accumulates to $O(\Delta t)$. $\blacksquare$

D.2 Construction of the Epistemic Laplacian

The Epistemic Laplacian $\mathbf{L}$ is derived from the steady-state approximation of the discretized system.

Definition D.3 (Epistemic Laplacian).
L_{ij} = \begin{cases} \lambda + \displaystyle\sum_{k=0}^{K} \sum_{\ell \neq j} A_{j\ell}(t_k, T) \Delta t & \text{if } i = j \\ -\displaystyle\sum_{k=0}^{K} A_{ij}(t_k, T) \Delta t & \text{if } i \neq j \end{cases} 

Proposition D.2 (Positive Definiteness). Under the condition $\lambda > \sum_{j \neq i} \sum_k A_{ij}\Delta t$, $\mathbf{L}$ is positive definite.

Proof. See Theorem 3 in main text. $\blacksquare$

D.3 Algorithmic Procedure for Theoretical Bounds

The following procedure outlines the analytical steps to verify the Sybil resistance bound (Theorem 5).

```
