Appendix F: Asymptotic Analysis and Limiting Cases

F.1 Large Network Limit ($N \to \infty$)

Proposition. To maintain stability as $N \to \infty$, the coupling constant must scale as $\gamma \sim O(1/N)$.

Proof. From Theorem 1, the contraction constant is $C_1 = (N-1)\bar{A}\gamma\bar{\kappa}(1+M_o) + \lambda$. For $T_0 < 1/C_1$ to remain non-vanishing as $N \to \infty$, we require $C_1$ to be bounded. Thus:
(N-1)\gamma \leq \text{const} \implies \gamma \leq \frac{\text{const}}{N-1}. \quad \blacksquare 

F.2 Infinite Time Horizon ($T \to \infty$)

Proposition. As $T \to \infty$, the Contribution Index grows linearly $C_i(T) \sim c_i T$ provided $\lambda > 0$.

Proof. From Theorem 2, $I_j(t)$ is bounded by $R$. Thus $\Phi_i(t)$ is bounded and converges to a steady state $\Phi_i^\infty$ satisfying:
\Phi_i^\infty = \gamma \kappa_i^\infty (1 + \operatorname{orig}_i^\infty)^+ \left(1 + \frac{I_i^\infty}{1 + I_i^\infty}\right), 


where $I_i^\infty$ solves $0 = \sum_{i \neq j} A_{ij}^\infty \Phi_i^\infty - \lambda I_j^\infty$.
Then:
C_i(T) = \int_0^T \Phi_i(\tau) d\tau = \Phi_i^\infty T + o(T). \quad \blacksquare 

F.3 No Decay Limit ($\lambda \to 0$)

Analysis. If $\lambda = 0$, the influence $I_j(t)$ accumulates indefinitely:
\frac{dI_j}{dt} = \sum_{i \neq j} \int_0^t A_{ij} \Phi_i \, d\tau. 


Integrating:
I_j(t) = I_j(0) + \int_0^t \int_0^s \sum_{i \neq j} A_{ij} \Phi_i \, d\tau ds. 


This grows at least linearly in $t$ if $\Phi_i$ has non-zero limit. In this limit, the spectral gap $\mu \to 0$ (Theorem 3), and the Epistemic Laplacian becomes singular. This confirms the necessity of $\lambda > 0$ for well-posedness.

F.4 No Semantic Component ($\operatorname{orig} \equiv 0, \operatorname{sim} \equiv 1$)

Analysis. The kernel reduces to:
A_{ij}(\tau, t) = \frac{e^{-\beta(t-\tau)}}{1 + \log(1 + |\mathcal{N}_i(\tau)|)}. 


The influence dynamics become:
\frac{dI_j}{dt} = \sum_{i \neq j} \int_0^t \frac{e^{-\beta(t-\tau)}}{1 + \log(1 + |\mathcal{N}_i(\tau)|)} \, d\tau - \lambda I_j(t). 


This recovers a log-damped Temporal PageRank. Removing the log-term ($1 + \log(1+|\mathcal{N}_i|) \to 1$) recovers standard Temporal PageRank (Rozenshtein and Gionis, 2016). This validates that our framework generalizes existing metrics.

